[[General (Australia)|General]] '''Peter Courtney Gration''' [[Order of Australia|AC]], [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (6 January 1932 &ndash; ) is an [[Australia]]n general who served in the positions of [[Chief of Army (Australia)|Chief of the General Staff]] and [[Chief of the Defence Force (Australia)|Chief of the Defence Force]]; the professional head of the [[Australian Army]] and [[Australian Defence Force]] respectively.

==Early life==
Gration was born in [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], on 6 January 1932.<ref name="VNR">{{cite web|url=http://www.vietnamroll.gov.au/VeteranDetails.aspx?VeteranId=1225990|title=GRATION, Peter Courtney|accessdaymonth=30 December|accessyear=2008|work=Nominal Roll of Vietnam Veterans|publisher=Commonwealth of Australia}}</ref> He attended [[Melbourne, Australia|Melbourne's]] [[Scotch College, Melbourne|Scotch College]] from 1945 until matriculation in 1948, during which time he was active in the school's cricket, football and athletics teams.<ref name="Scotch">{{cite web|url=http://www.scotch.vic.edu.au/Gscot/07maygs/47.htm|title=General Peter Gration AC OBE (<U+2019>48)|accessdaymonth=30 December|accessyear=2008|work=Great Scot|publisher=Scotch College}}</ref>

==Military career==
Accepted into the [[Royal Military College, Duntroon]], Gration began his course at the college in 1949. He graduated as a [[lieutenant]] three years later with the Queen's Medal, and was allocated to the [[Royal Australian Engineers]]. During the proceeding two years, Gration was a resident student at [[Ormond College (University of Melbourne)|Ormond College]] in the [[University of Melbourne]] where he completed a [[Bachelor of Engineering|Bachelor of Civil Engineering]] degree; Gration subsequently completed a [[Bachelor of Arts]] and [[Bachelor of Economics]] at the [[University of Queensland]] in later years.<ref name="Scotch"/>

Gration saw active service during the [[Malayan Emergency]], before attending the [[British Army]] [[Staff College, Camberley]] in 1964.<ref name="Scotch"/> He completed a tour of duty during the [[Vietnam War]] between 1969 and 1970, during which time he was posted as commanding officer of the 1st Australian Civil Affairs Unit with the rank of [[lieutenant colonel]].<ref name="VNR"/> For his "distinguished services" in Vietnam, Gration was awarded an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1971.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=45276|date=8 January 1971|startpage=362|accessdaymonth=30 December|accessyear=2008}}</ref>

In 1973, Gration was appointed Director of Engineers. Following this three year stint, he was posted to a course at the [[United States Army]] [[U.S. Army War College|War College]]. In 1984, Gration was awarded an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] in the [[Australia Day]] Honours List for his service as Assistant Chief of the of the Defence Force Staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=879670&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Gration, Peter Courtney (AO)|accessdaymonth=30 December|accessyear=2008|work=It's an Honour|publisher=Commonwealth of Australia}}</ref> Later that same year, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant General (Australia)|lieutenant general]] and appointed Chief of the General Staff; a position marking him as the professonal head of the Australian Army.<ref name="Scotch"/>

Promoted to general, Gration was appointed Chief of the Defence Force in 1987.<ref name="Scotch"/> In the Australia Day Honours of 1988, he was upgraded to a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=879446&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Gration, Peter Courtney (AC)|accessdaymonth=30 December|accessyear=2008|work=It's an Honour|publisher=Commonwealth of Australia}}</ref> Following forty-four years of service, Gration retired from the Australian Army and active military service in 1993.<ref name="Scotch"/>

==Retirement==
Since his retirement from the army, Gration has held various senior positions in companies and charities, including: Chairman of the Civil Aviation Authority, Chairman of the Council of the [[Australian War Memorial]], Chairman of the Management Committee of Transfield Defence Systems, Chairman of the Advisory Board of the [[Australian Defence College]], a Director of Tenix Pty Ltd, Chairman of Tenix Toll Defence Logistics Pty Ltd, Founding Chairman of the General Sir [[John Monash]] Foundation, and National President of Toc H.<ref name="Scotch"/>

In 1993, Gration was awarded an hononary [[Doctor of Science]] from the [[University of New South Wales]]. During 1994&ndash;1995, Gration served as a consultant to the Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet and had primary responsibility for negotiation of a security agreement with [[Indonesia]]. During this time, he was appointed Honorary Colonel of the [[Melbourne University Regiment]], and made Representative Colonel Commandant of the Royal Australian Engineers during 2000.<ref name="Scotch"/>

Since the [[2003 Invasion of Iraq]], Gration has been open in his criticism of Australia's involvement during the war. In an article he wrote for [[The Age|''The Age'']], Gration declared: "...&nbsp;there are insufficient grounds for war, which is unnecessary and may lead to unpredictable and potentially disastrous consequences. It is not in Australia's interests to take part in such a war.".<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Gration|title=The case against war with Iraq|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/01/01/1041196687995.html|publisher=The Age|date=2 January 2003|accessdate=30 December 2008}}</ref> He was awarded the inaugural Peace Prize from the Australian Medical Association for the Prevention of War in April 2005 for his "outspoken criticism".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpd.org.au/user/pgration|title=Peter Gration|accessdaymonth=30 December|accessyear=2008|publisher=Centre for Policy Development}}</ref>

Married with two sons, Gration is an Hononary Fellow of the Institution of Engineers, Australia, and a Fellow of the Australian Academy of Technological Sciences and Engineering.<ref name="Scotch"/>

